08 - Linear regression and correlation

Francisco E. Fonturbel

02/August/2022

Linear regression

So far, we have dealt with a continuous response variable contrasted against categorical predictors. But in many cases we have continuous predictors. For example, we may assess the effect of temperature on enzymatic activity based on an experimental trial. We know from the books that many enzymes perform better at certain temperatures, and we want to test it in our laboratory. So, lets load the example file with temperature and enzymatic activity data.

data<-read.csv("data/08_enzactivity.csv", header = T, sep = ",")
attach(data)
head(data)
##   X temperature enzactiv
## 1 1    3.862647 2.314489
## 2 2    4.979381 3.433490
## 3 3    4.923957 4.599373
## 4 4    3.214372 2.791114
## 5 5    7.196409 5.596398
## 6 6    3.729643 2.458556

Before fitting a linear model, we will examine the distribution of the response variable (i.e., enzymatic activity) to assess if it follows a normal distribution:

hist(enzactiv, col = "dodgerblue1")

shapiro.test(enzactiv)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  enzactiv
## W = 0.98705, p-value = 0.0002095

Well, it is more or less normal

Linear relationships

Linear models are very common in science, as many of the relationships that we assume that variables increase or decrease along other predictors, resembling a linear function y = ax + b

Lets take a look of our data:

plot(enzactiv~temperature, col = "firebrick2", xlab = "Temperature (C)", ylab = "Enzymatic activity")

Well, it clearly resembles a linear relationship. But we are scientists and we assess hard data and not merely plots lets make a linear model for it!

mod1<-lm(enzactiv~temperature)
summary(mod1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = enzactiv ~ temperature)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.02479 -0.48526  0.04078  0.45898  2.37805 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  0.20427    0.08884   2.299   0.0219 *  
## temperature  0.71383    0.01854  38.505   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.7181 on 496 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7493, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7488 
## F-statistic:  1483 on 1 and 496 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

Well, well, well our linear relationship is significant indeed. Enzymatic activity is positively influenced by temperature, as the books said.

But, what a linear model does? It looks for the linear function that fits better to our data. Lets plot it:

plot(enzactiv~temperature, xlab = "Temperature (C)", ylab = "Enzymatic activity")
abline(lm(enzactiv~temperature), col = "firebrick2", lwd = 3)

so, let me introduce a new concept here: residuals. The difference of each data point to the trend line is a residual. A linear regression can be assessed examining how well the resulting model fits our data. One first approach is to examine R-squared, as it gets closer to 1 the regression is optimal. In this case, our R-squared value is 0.7493218, which indicates a pretty decent fit. But lets take a look on our residuals:

plot(density(resid(mod1))) #A density plot

qqnorm(resid(mod1)) # A quantile normal plot - good for checking normality
qqline(resid(mod1))

Good, our residuals look good. In linear models, the normality of the residuals is more important than the normality of the raw variables themselves.

shapiro.test(resid(mod1))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  resid(mod1)
## W = 0.99677, p-value = 0.4237

Great! we are good to go.
